               <msContents>
                  <msItem xml:id="MS_Hamilton_35-item1" n="1">
                     <locus>(fol. 1)</locus>
                     <rubric>Questiones et dubia pro religiosis vtilia</rubric>
                     <incipit>In
                     nomine ... Ad mandatum et beneplacitum venerabilis patris domini abbatis de
                     Claratumba</incipit>
                     <incipit>Queritur
                     volenti ingredi religionem</incipit>
                     <note>In 24 parts. At fol. 158v is 'Epistola Bernardi
                        in libello de Mundi contemptu', addressed to the abbot of Cluny.</note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem xml:id="MS_Hamilton_35-item2" n="2">
                     <locus>(fol. 160)</locus>
                     <author key="person_22933358"><supplied>Jacobus de Clusa</supplied></author>
                     <title>De temptatione et consolatione religiosorum</title>
                     <rubric>De temptacionibus &#x0026; solacionibus religiosorum</rubric>
                     <incipit>Instantibus tuis patribus</incipit>
                     <note>In 16 dialogues between Magister and
                        Discipulus, with preface: at end is 'Planctus Peccatoris' beg. 'Scribis
                        contra me': fol. 240v)</note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem xml:id="MS_Hamilton_35-item3" n="3">
                     <locus>(fol. 245)</locus>
                     <rubric>...Oculus Religiosorum</rubric>
                     <incipit>In nomine ... Multorum Deo
                     militare cupiencium</incipit>
                     <note>in 28 chapters: at end in a different but contemporary
                        hand is 'Anno Domini M째 cccc째 xliij째 infra octauas Natiuitatis gloriose
                        Virginis ... Marie.' Then follow 'Formula reformandi religiones ab
                        obseruancia lapsas' beg. 'Quia teste ore veri-tatis': fol. 286): 'Epistola
                        Henrici de Hassia' (beg. 'Honorabili ... Literas caritatis vestre': fol.
                        292): a poem on the vanity of earthly delights (beg. 'Si tibi diuicias
                        cumules metalla, quid inde?': fol. 293v).</note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem xml:id="MS_Hamilton_35-item4" n="4">
                     <locus>(fol. 295)</locus>
                     <rubric>...Tractatus de bona voluntate</rubric>
                     <incipit>Cum omnium fructuum
                     nobilitas</incipit>
                     <note>in 22 chapters: at end 'Annis [sic] Domini 1444째 in octaua
                        Epyphanie, etc.'</note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem xml:id="MS_Hamilton_35-item5" n="5">
                     <locus>(fol. 323v)</locus>
                     <rubric>De perfectione Religiosorum</rubric>
                     <incipit>Cum cognitio et
                     desiderium finis</incipit>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem xml:id="MS_Hamilton_35-item6" n="6">
                     <locus>(fol. 331v)</locus>
                     <rubric>De arte curandi Vicia</rubric>
                     <incipit>Isaac sanctus patriarcha</incipit>
                     <note>At
                     the foot of the first column is '1444 Mich'', i.e. Michaelmas (?).</note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem xml:id="MS_Hamilton_35-item7" n="7">
                     <locus>(fol. 340v)</locus>
                     <rubric>De profectu in vita spirituali</rubric>
                     <incipit>Spiritualis vir omnia
                     diiudicans</incipit>
                     <note> At the foot of the first column is '1444', and at the foot of
                        the last '1444. hedwigis', i.e. St. Hedwig's day (?).</note>
                  </msItem>
